# Angular & TypeScript Development Rules

## Angular Best Practices

### Components and Architecture
- Always use standalone components (Angular 20 style)
- Use `inject()` function instead of constructor injection for better zoneless compatibility
- Prefer signals over RxJS observables when possible (Angular 20 signals API)
- Use `OnPush` change detection strategy when appropriate
- Keep components focused on presentation logic only

### Services
- Use services for business logic and state management
- Services should be provided at the root level unless specific scoping is needed
- Use signals for reactive state management in services
- Prefer `inject()` function over constructor injection

### TypeScript Configuration
- Strict mode is enabled - always type everything explicitly
- No implicit any types allowed
- Use strict null checks
- Enable `noImplicitReturns`, `noFallthroughCasesInSwitch`
- Use `noPropertyAccessFromIndexSignature` for safer property access

### Testing
- Use Vitest for all TypeScript/JavaScript testing (not Jasmine/Jest)
- Test files should have `.spec.ts` extension
- Use `vitest/globals` types (configured in tsconfig.json)
- Write unit tests for services and components
- Mock Tauri API calls in tests
- Ensure all unit tests pass before moving on to new work

### Package Management
- Always use `pnpm` instead of npm or yarn
- Run `pnpm install` to add dependencies
- Use `pnpm add -D` for dev dependencies

### JavaScript Module Files
- **ALWAYS use `.mjs` extension for JavaScript configuration files**
- Never use `.js` or `.cjs` extensions for JavaScript files
- All JavaScript files must use ESM (ES Modules) syntax
- Use `import`/`export` instead of `require`/`module.exports`
- Package.json is configured with `"type": "module"` for ESM-only mode

### Code Style
- Follow Angular style guide conventions
- Use SCSS for component styles (configured in angular.json)
- Use async/await instead of promise chains when possible
- Prefer readonly properties when values don't change
- Use public readonly signals exposed from services

### Error Handling
- Handle errors in async operations properly
- Use try/catch blocks for async/await
- Provide meaningful error messages to users
- Log errors appropriately (console.error for development)

### Angular Routing
- Use standalone route configuration
- Prefer functional guards and resolvers
- Keep routes organized in app.routes.ts

### Tauri Integration
- Use `@tauri-apps/api` for Tauri commands
- Handle Tauri command responses as Promises
- Use proper TypeScript types for Tauri responses

### Performance
- Use OnPush change detection where possible
- Prefer signals over observables for simple reactive state
- Lazy load routes when appropriate
- Optimize bundle size by importing only needed modules

### Documentation
- Add JSDoc comments for public methods
- Document complex business logic
- Include parameter and return type descriptions
